---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Chapter from "../components/Chapter.astro";
import Lesson from "../components/Lesson.astro";
import Artifact from "../components/Artifact.astro";
---

<Base title="Navigating the Idea Maze | Tools for Sovereignty">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <header class="container hero">
    <h1 class="hero-title">
      Navigating the<br />Idea Maze
    </h1>
    <div class="hero-intro">
      <p>
        Tools for Sovereignty turns 1 today. We spent the last year navigating the
        <a class="inline-link" href="https://cdixon.org/2013/08/04/the-idea-maze" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">idea maze</a>.
        We shipped 6 products all anchored around context: what makes AI truly useful to you. We started Tools for Sovereignty to give people control over their context.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- The Maze -->
  <div class="container maze" id="maze">

    <Chapter date="December 2024" title="What Did You Get Done Today?" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Product: A Slack bot automating standup.
      </p>
      <p>
        Problem: Companies waste a lot of time on coordination whilst all the context already exists.
      </p>
      <p>
        Description: A Slack bot using LLMs to aggregate the work done across different tools.
      </p>
      <p>
        GTM: Founder sales.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        First swing at sovereignty over work signal: extract context that already lives in your tools. LLMs and MCP weren't ready. Right intuition, eighteen months early.
      </Lesson>
      <figure class="chapter-figure">
        <img src="/slack-bot-screenshot.jpg" alt="Slack bot daily summary" class="chapter-image" />
      </figure>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="January - April 2025" title="The Worldcoin Bet" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Product: Mini-apps on World App.
      </p>
      <p>
        Opportunity: World App was emerging as a novel superapp.
      </p>
      <p>
        GTM: Build the best AI apps on World leveraging personal context —
        <a class="inline-link" href="https://x.com/arthaud_/status/1883950196159353191" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">got to 250k users</a> in the span of a few months.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Built consumer AI apps. The 250k users came back for personalisation, which is just context applied at the user level. Wrong audience for a B2B sovereignty story, but this is where we learned context is the moat.
      </Lesson>
      <figure class="chapter-figure">
        <img src="/worldcoin-screenshot.jpg" alt="Sage — #1 AI app on World" class="chapter-image" />
      </figure>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="May - September 2025" title="Private Memory Infrastructure" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Product: Private memory infrastructure sold to AI apps.
      </p>
      <p>
        Problem: With our apps we realised early that memory was the moat for AI apps — users should control it and be able to share it across apps.
      </p>
      <p>
        Solution: SDK/API & MCP server for apps to personalise their LLM-based offerings, privacy guarantees via TEEs.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Apps wanted the context, not the privacy story. Selling sovereignty as a feature instead of an outcome was the mistake.
      </Lesson>
      <p>
        We wrote a
        <a class="inline-link" href="https://x.com/arthaud_/status/1945155464620048607" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">manifesto</a>
        about why the privacy frame mattered, then learned the buyer didn't care.
      </p>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="September - December 2025" title="The Identity Play" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Product: IAM provider with context seeding.
      </p>
      <p>
        Problem: Users don't have to reintroduce themselves to every app.
      </p>
      <p>
        Solution: <a class="inline-link" href="https://x.com/arthaud_/status/1981768176049246422" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Identity provider</a> with context seeding — think Poke's onboarding as a service.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Context isn't a layer underneath the app. It is the app. No founder wants to outsource the most valuable part of their product to an IAM provider, no matter how good the seeding is.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="January - March 2026" title="Context Aggregator" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Products: MCP context aggregator, initially for individuals, then for companies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Problem: Your context is tied to an LLM provider, you should be able to port it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Solution: An extension to your AI apps that syncs them to the relevant context.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Context reconciliation is hard. The bigger lesson: context is plumbing, and plumbing isn't a product. Sell the outcome of sovereignty (your work gets done with your data) not the pipe.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="April 2026" title="Coworker in Slack" status="active-path">
      <p>
        Product: Agent that lives in Slack and gets work done for you.
      </p>
      <p>
        Problem: Most agents today are single player, require technical knowledge to adopt and aren't proactive.
      </p>
      <p>
        Solution: A digital coworker that knows your company, adapts to how you work and is accessible directly in your team communication tool.
      </p>
      <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <Artifact label="Try it here" type="demo" href="https://mio.xyz" />
      </div>
      <p>
        We're a small team of founders obsessed with product and sweating the details.
      </p>
      <p>
        Your context, your team, your perimeter. Sovereignty as outcome, not as pitch.
      </p>
    </Chapter>

  </div>

</Base>
